attributes.background:
The population density of England is almost double that of Germany and quadruple that of France.

The population density in England at the last census was 383 people per km².

This compares with a population density of 271/km² in Fife where Gordon Brown is an MP, and just 65/km² in Scotland as a whole.

These new towns should be built in Scotland so that Scotland can benefit from the increase in population and the positive environmental effects of these fantastic new eco-homes.

The sites currently proposed by the Government are as follows:

Bordon, Hampshire;
Coltishall, Norfolk;
Curborough, Staffordshire;
Elsenham, Essex;
Ford, West Sussex;
Hanley Grange, Cambridgeshire;
Imerys, near St Austell, Cornwall;
Leeds city region, West Yorkshire;
Manby, Lincolnshire;
Marston Vale and New Marston, Bedfordshire;
Middle Quinton, Warwickshire;
Pennbury, Leicestershire;
Rossington, South Yorkshire;
Rushcliffe, Nottinghamshire, and;
Weston Otmoor, Oxfordshire.
